but did she give you
the details?

14:08.792 --> 14:10.959
Did she fill in the blanks
that make a story a story?

14:10.959 --> 14:12.625
Because my guess is

14:12.625 --> 14:14.166
there's a lot you don't know,
Dawson.

14:14.583 --> 14:16.291
My guess is you don't know
the half of it.

14:18.792 --> 14:19.542
[DOOR OPENS]

14:21.000 --> 14:22.458
Joey,
I really need to talk to you.

14:22.792 --> 14:24.542
Look, my life is rapidly
becoming a punch line

14:24.542 --> 14:25.542
to some seriously
disturbed joke--

14:25.542 --> 14:27.875
Shh! If you wake him up,
your life will be over!

14:30.500 --> 14:31.875
So, what is the problem?

14:32.625 --> 14:34.333
Okay. You know how I yesterday
I said that everything

14:34.333 --> 14:35.792
between Jen and me
was great, was fine?

14:35.792 --> 14:37.417
Well, no, it's not. It's a mess.

14:37.417 --> 14:39.000
Her ex-boyfriend from New York
is here,

14:39.000 --> 14:40.166
and he's staying at my house.

14:42.000 --> 14:43.917
Oh, so that's who that cute guy
was in school yesterday.

14:43.917 --> 14:45.125
[SIGHS]
You're not helping.

14:46.667 --> 14:48.166
Look, what's the big deal?
I mean, I thought

14:48.166 --> 14:50.333
you were with Jen.
You guys are a couple, right?

14:50.333 --> 14:51.041
Yeah. Of course.

14:51.458 --> 14:52.166
So?

14:53.041 --> 14:54.000
Well, you know,
it's just that Mr. Smooth

14:54.000 --> 14:56.083
rides into town,
and all of a sudden bowling

14:56.083 --> 14:57.625
started to sound pretty lame.

14:57.625 --> 14:59.750
Dawson, bowling always
sounds lame.

15:00.000 --> 15:01.208
[SIGHS]
Look, um...

15:02.208 --> 15:03.834
Billy's staying at my house,
which I hate,

15:04.250 --> 15:06.667
Okay? But if I kick him out,
I look petty and insecure.

15:06.667 --> 15:08.333
If I-- if I let him stay,

15:09.041 --> 15:09.834
I feel like a patsy.

15:10.208 --> 15:11.417
I mean...
[SIGHS]

15:11.417 --> 15:12.166
Well, uh...

15:13.417 --> 15:15.834
I'm beginning to think
relationship problems run
in my family.

15:16.750 --> 15:18.375
Dawson, I hate to break
it to you,

15:18.375 --> 15:20.583
but your problems really aren't
that original.

15:20.583 --> 15:22.708
You know, divorce
and dysfunction run rampant

15:22.708 --> 15:23.583
in this town, so I--

15:23.583 --> 15:24.792
Dysfunction I can handle, okay?

15:24.792 --> 15:25.542
Divorce...

15:27.250 --> 15:29.208
How much pain and humiliation

15:29.208 --> 15:31.375
can a relationship endure
before it's reached

15:31.375 --> 15:32.375
the point of no return?

15:34.208 --> 15:36.375
Are we talking about the father
or the son here?

15:37.041 --> 15:37.792
[SIGHS]

15:40.625 --> 15:42.417
Dawson, relax.

15:42.417 --> 15:43.417
Don't worry about it, you know?

15:43.417 --> 15:45.291
It's all gonna blow over,
and you're gonna be on

15:45.291 --> 15:47.208
to bigger and better problems
before you know it.

15:47.583 --> 15:48.750
You think so?

15:48.750 --> 15:49.792
Don't worry.

15:50.125 --> 15:51.625
I should...sit tight?

15:52.291 --> 15:54.041
It's all gonna be fine.

15:56.750 --> 15:58.375
Right. Thanks.

15:58.708 --> 15:59.667
You're the best.

16:01.458 --> 16:02.208
[DOOR SLAMS]

16:03.917 --> 16:05.208
[BABY CRIES]

16:05.750 --> 16:06.458
Ohh...

16:15.583 --> 16:18.125
JEN: You know, I really did
want to let you know, Dawson,

16:18.125 --> 16:20.250
how much I appreciate
your generosity

16:20.250 --> 16:22.500
in giving him a place to crash
and everything.

16:22.500 --> 16:23.291
Billy's not exactly here

16:23.291 --> 16:25.250
to watch the leaves
change color,

16:25.250 --> 16:26.125
is he, Jen?

16:27.875 --> 16:29.083
No. Didn't think so.

16:30.250 --> 16:31.750
I think he's here
to get you back.

16:33.250 --> 16:35.750
I don't know whether you think
I'm...super-evolved

16:35.750 --> 16:37.917
or just plain oblivious
to everything, but you know
this is really--

16:37.917 --> 16:39.917
Look, Dawson, I told--
I told him it's over with us.

16:39.917 --> 16:41.625
I told him everything
about us, you know that.

16:41.625 --> 16:42.667
I don't think he's
getting the message,

16:42.667 --> 16:44.625
and quite frankly,
I don't think you want him to.

16:45.125 --> 16:46.458
Hey, Dawson, um...

16:46.792 --> 16:48.458
I don't want to lie
to you, so...

16:48.792 --> 16:51.458
Yeah, Billy still has feelings
for me.

16:52.333 --> 16:54.959
I mean...we never really got
a chance to say goodbye.

16:54.959 --> 16:57.291
My parents threw me out
of New York so fast

16:57.291 --> 16:58.792
there was never any time
for closure.

17:00.500 --> 17:01.625
I thought you wanted to make a
break from all those guys who
sexualized you way too young.

17:01.625 --> 17:04.708
But-- but Billy wasn't one
of them. He was the only guy

17:04.708 --> 17:06.125
who ever treated me
with respect.

17:06.125 --> 17:07.583
He-- he treated me well.

17:08.040 --> 17:09.125
So, you're going back
to him?

17:10.125 --> 17:11.458
[SIGHS]
I'm...

17:11.959 --> 17:13.083
You have to think
about that?

17:13.375 --> 17:15.165
It-- it's just not that simple,
alright?

17:15.165 --> 17:16.208
It's confusing, okay?

17:16.208 --> 17:18.083
We're invited to a party tonight
at Cliff Elliott's,

17:18.083 --> 17:19.333
and I want you to come
with me.

17:19.625 --> 17:20.959
I want things to go
back to normal,

17:20.959 --> 17:22.290
and I want Billy gone.

17:22.290 --> 17:24.333
Look, I can't just send him
away like that.

17:24.333 --> 17:26.625
Right, of course. He's treated
you with nothing but respect,

17:27.000 --> 17:29.000
but you know what, Jen?
Last time I checked, so did I.

17:30.166 --> 17:31.708
And how do I get repaid?
By having the guy

17:31.708 --> 17:33.250
who's had you everywhere
from Battery Park

17:33.250 --> 17:35.458
to your parents' bed dumped
on me as my new bunkmate.

17:35.458 --> 17:37.500
Dawson, come on!
Be fair to me, alright?

17:38.333 --> 17:40.333
Look, this isn't the easiest
situation in the world

17:40.333 --> 17:41.208
for me either, I mean...

17:42.166 --> 17:44.333
I mean, imagine if some
ex-girlfriend of yours

17:44.333 --> 17:46.500
suddenly showed up to town
and just put everything

17:46.750 --> 17:48.000
in a whirlwind.
How would you feel--

17:48.000 --> 17:49.750
You know what, Jen?
That's impossible, okay?

17:49.750 --> 17:51.500
Because I don't have
an ex-girlfriend.

17:51.875 --> 17:53.875
You're my girlfriend,
my first and only.

17:53.875 --> 17:55.750
All I'm trying to do is prevent
Billy's ex

17:55.750 --> 17:57.125
from becoming my ex, too.

17:57.500 --> 17:59.750
My feelings for you haven't
changed, Dawson?

17:59.750 --> 18:03.500
Can't you see that?
Try and understand.

18:05.708 --> 18:06.959
Unfortunately, I think I do.

18:11.792 --> 18:15.375
[HORROR SCREAMS]

18:15.375 --> 18:16.375
[BELL CHIMES]

18:18.375 --> 18:19.041
-[MUTES TV]
-Look...

18:19.792 --> 18:21.041
I need to rent
The English Patient.

18:22.208 --> 18:24.583
May I suggest to you a movie
that does not completely blow?

18:24.583 --> 18:25.875
No, because it was on cable
last night,

18:25.875 --> 18:26.875
and it put the baby to sleep.

18:28.000 --> 18:28.667
In fact, it's the only thing
that's put the baby to sleep

18:28.667 --> 18:29.708
because the baby never sleeps.

18:29.708 --> 18:30.750
And if the baby doesn't sleep,
then I don't sleep,

18:30.750 --> 18:33.041
and if I don't sleep,
I get angry. I get irritable,

18:33.041 --> 18:34.458
and I no longer maintain
my sunny disposition.

18:34.458 --> 18:37.000
So, Pacey, if you have
the slightest bit of decency,

18:37.000 --> 18:38.208
you'll rent this movie to me
immediately

18:38.208 --> 18:40.708
and bring 181 minutes of peace
in my otherwise wretched life.

18:41.542 --> 18:44.375
-Please?
-Alright. But...

18:45.375 --> 18:49.000
in my professional opinion,
you don't need a video store.

18:49.792 --> 18:50.708
You need a pharmacy.

18:53.583 --> 18:55.834
Anyway...I hear Jen's ex

18:55.834 --> 18:57.166
has been
lurking around Capeside.

18:57.917 --> 18:59.625
Met this strapping
young fellow yet?

18:59.625 --> 19:01.417
Oh, yeah.
He's a real charmer.

19:01.417 --> 19:02.250
Just about lost 3 toes

19:02.250 --> 19:04.041
to a pair of his steel-belted
radials.

19:05.417 --> 19:07.542
So, what's the party line?
Think she'll go back to him?

19:07.792 --> 19:09.041
Return to her wanton
New York ways?

19:09.417 --> 19:10.708
You know, I really don't know.

19:11.750 --> 19:12.625
But...

19:12.625 --> 19:14.250
If Jen did ditch Dawson
for Billy the Kid,

19:14.250 --> 19:16.083
wouldn't that please a certain
someone we both know?

19:17.083 --> 19:18.166
You know me, Pacey,
I mean...

19:19.333 --> 19:20.458
I'm not one to stand in the way
of true love, you know...

19:21.542 --> 19:23.250
But if...if Jen has a connection
to this guy, which...

19:23.500 --> 19:24.834
seems like she does,
you know...

19:25.250 --> 19:26.458
What can we do about it?

19:26.458 --> 19:27.542
Look, Joey,

19:28.000 --> 19:28.959
I've never really taken

19:28.959 --> 19:31.125
a particular interest
in your life 'cause...

19:31.792 --> 19:34.458
frankly, your life has never
been particularly interesting,

19:34.458 --> 19:35.208
but...

19:36.000 --> 19:36.959
there is one thing I need
to know.

19:37.917 --> 19:39.625
You're really really  enjoying
the fact

19:39.625 --> 19:41.250
that Jen's ex is in town,
aren't you?

19:41.542 --> 19:42.959
Well, it's intriguing, Pacey,

19:42.959 --> 19:44.417
I mean, even you have
to admit that.

19:44.417 --> 19:45.208
But you know what?

19:46.125 --> 19:47.083
This is the wedge
you've been waiting for

19:47.083 --> 19:49.291
that's gonna drive Jen
and Dawson apart, right?

19:49.291 --> 19:51.542
No, Pacey, you're such--
It-- It's--

19:51.542 --> 19:53.500
It's not like that at all.
You don't know what you're--

19:53.500 --> 19:54.875
The 3 of us, we've been friends
too long,

19:54.875 --> 19:57.500
and up until now, I've just kind
of stood idly by

19:57.500 --> 19:58.792
and watched this all go down,

19:58.792 --> 20:00.792
but it's time to lay this
on the line, okay?

20:01.375 --> 20:04.458
You have some raging
hormonal obsession

20:04.458 --> 20:05.667
for our friend Dawson.

20:05.667 --> 20:08.500
And you just can't wait to get
your hooks into him but good,

20:08.500 --> 20:10.166
Can you? Huh?

20:12.083 --> 20:12.959
Bite me, Pacey.

20:15.000 --> 20:16.333
♪ Busted... ♪

20:18.250 --> 20:19.667
Hey, be kind. Rewind.

20:23.250 --> 20:25.166
[DOOR OPENS]
What is the big deal?

20:25.583 --> 20:26.708
The instruction
was pretty basic.

20:26.708 --> 20:28.708
It should never be more than
3 feet away from your buddy

20:28.708 --> 20:29.583
at any time.

20:29.583 --> 20:30.625
Oh, now that's ironic.

20:31.625 --> 20:33.000
Me getting bitched
at for floating away from you.

20:34.208 --> 20:35.375
GALE: The teacher said that
if there was a leak in the tank

20:35.375 --> 20:38.166
and the oxygen ran out,
or if I got caught
in a kelp bed.

20:38.166 --> 20:39.834
MITCH: We were in a pool, Gale.
Alright?

20:40.250 --> 20:41.375
What's the worst
that could happen?

20:41.375 --> 20:42.834
We bump our heads
on a water slide?

20:43.417 --> 20:44.667
GALE: That is not the point.

20:45.417 --> 20:47.792
Look, I can't do this
by myself.

20:47.792 --> 20:50.041
So, if you're gonna fight this
therapy every step of the way,

20:50.041 --> 20:51.583
then we're both just wasting
our time,

20:51.583 --> 20:52.708
so let me know, Mitch.

20:52.708 --> 20:55.083
Because if that is the case,
then we might as well--

20:55.083 --> 20:58.208
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

20:58.208 --> 21:02.708
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

21:05.875 --> 21:06.917
JOEY: Can I take
your order?

21:06.917 --> 21:08.792
Oh, uh...
let's see, um...

21:08.792 --> 21:10.333
You know everything's
really good.

21:11.375 --> 21:12.708
Uh, um...

21:12.708 --> 21:14.041
Hey, Joey,
Table 5.

21:14.041 --> 21:17.291
Miss, uh, I think I'll
just have some...

21:17.959 --> 21:19.959
-Coffee to start and um--
-Alright, one second.

21:21.375 --> 21:23.333
-Can I take your order?
-Already ordered, ma'am.

21:23.708 --> 21:26.125
This is Table 8, Joey.
I said Table 5.

21:26.125 --> 21:26.875
Okay.

21:26.875 --> 21:28.917
WOMAN: Miss,
that coffee, please?

21:28.917 --> 21:30.417
Alright, in a second.

21:30.417 --> 21:32.208
Uh...just a second.

21:33.500 --> 21:34.458
Hey, Joe.

21:34.458 --> 21:36.500
Oh, thank you, Satan
for completing this night

21:36.500 --> 21:38.000
of horrors by sending one
of your disciples

21:38.000 --> 21:38.708
to finish me off.

21:38.708 --> 21:40.583
Um, what are you doing tonight?

21:40.583 --> 21:42.208
MAN: Excuse me,
I didn't order this!

21:42.625 --> 21:44.792
Forget I said that,
but I was just out

21:44.792 --> 21:46.917
looking for a date,
and since I couldn't find one,

21:47.166 --> 21:48.750
-I thought of you.
-Oh.

21:48.750 --> 21:49.708
So, how's about it?

21:49.708 --> 21:51.250
You wanna go crash a
beach party with me, huh?

21:51.250 --> 21:53.166
Oh, gee whiz. You know,
as much as that sounds

21:53.166 --> 21:55.083
like so much fun,
you know, I'm kinda busy.

21:56.250 --> 21:58.875
-Come on, Joe. It'll be fun.
-Yeah.

22:00.000 --> 22:01.959
After I serve the hundred
millionth seafood platter,

22:01.959 --> 22:04.333
finish picking the broken glass
out of the ice machine,

22:04.583 --> 22:06.458
scrape the mung out
of the fry-o-laters,

22:06.458 --> 22:08.458
I was thinking of maybe
taking my tip money,

22:08.458 --> 22:11.083
flying to the Canary Islands
and opening an offshore account.

22:12.083 --> 22:14.333
What do you think of that?
Sorry.

22:14.333 --> 22:16.041
Y-You know,
when's the last--

22:16.041 --> 22:18.458
Okay, alright, alright.
You know, wait, Joey,

22:18.458 --> 22:19.917
When was the last time
you went out and had

22:19.917 --> 22:20.834
some fun, alright?

22:21.125 --> 22:21.792
Don't ask.

22:22.208 --> 22:23.125
[DISHES CLATTERING]

22:23.125 --> 22:25.333
Besides, Dawson's gonna
be there, alright?

22:25.333 --> 22:27.959
-Big whoop.
-Alone, Joey.

22:30.166 --> 22:30.959
Go.

22:33.291 --> 22:34.166
It's swamped.

22:34.166 --> 22:35.458
Sara's coming in to cover.

22:35.458 --> 22:37.041
Yeah, but you need me.
I mean, she can't handle

22:37.041 --> 22:38.125
-this by herself--
-Goodbye.

22:38.542 --> 22:39.834
Thank you.

22:40.333 --> 22:41.792
Come on, come on,
come on.

22:43.458 --> 22:44.500
Party on, Bessie.

22:47.291 --> 22:49.125
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

22:51.125 --> 22:52.041
[KNOCK ON DOOR]
[DOOR OPENS]

22:52.041 --> 22:53.583
-MITCH: Dawson?
-Yeah?

22:54.041 --> 22:54.792
Hey.

22:56.458 --> 22:57.500
Hey.

22:57.500 --> 22:59.458
-How's it going?
-Um...

23:00.875 --> 23:03.333
-Complicated, you?
-Complicated.

23:04.333 --> 23:06.333
Squarely in the midst
of what Dr. Keenan would refer

23:06.333 --> 23:07.959
to as Stage 4.

23:08.417 --> 23:09.333
Stage 4.

23:11.000 --> 23:12.708
Dare I ask what Stage 5 is?

23:14.500 --> 23:16.417
Anyway... [CLEARS THROAT]
On to you.

23:16.417 --> 23:17.542
Where's Billy the Kid?

23:18.500 --> 23:19.250
Um...

23:20.375 --> 23:22.834
Best guess? Probably hanging
out with his ex-girlfriend,

23:23.500 --> 23:24.834
who happens to be
my current girlfriend,

23:24.834 --> 23:26.166
which means,
among other things,

23:26.166 --> 23:28.000
that I'll be attending
tonight's barbecue solo,

23:28.917 --> 23:32.250
while Jen spends the afternoon
with my new roommate.

23:33.667 --> 23:34.458
[CHAIR CREAKS]

23:35.458 --> 23:36.875
I wonder what stage
Dr. Keenan would put us in.

23:37.542 --> 23:38.458
Well, high school.

23:39.041 --> 23:39.917
Let's face it, Dad.

23:40.875 --> 23:42.125
We're a couple
of nice guys,

23:43.583 --> 23:45.208
which stopped being a desirable
character trait
about half a century ago.

23:45.959 --> 23:46.917
Dawson,

23:48.250 --> 23:49.750
I am the last person
who should be giving

23:49.750 --> 23:51.708
you or anyone else romance tips.

23:51.708 --> 23:55.041
However, it seems
that every relationship

23:55.041 --> 23:57.542
produces its share
of disappointments

23:57.542 --> 23:59.875
and insecurity and pain.

24:00.125 --> 24:03.208
Anyone who's never been hurt
is either very lucky

24:04.208 --> 24:05.375
or very lonely.

24:06.959 --> 24:07.917
The trick is...

24:09.250 --> 24:10.208
To get through it.

24:11.125 --> 24:11.917
How?

24:12.500 --> 24:15.041
Compromise, tears...

24:16.208 --> 24:18.041
Scuba lessons
at the local "Y."

24:18.708 --> 24:19.834
Different for everyone.

24:20.166 --> 24:21.083
And that works?

24:23.458 --> 24:25.041
I have no idea, kid.

24:26.792 --> 24:28.083
[CHUCKLES]

24:28.625 --> 24:30.083
No idea whatsoever.

24:31.959 --> 24:34.625
[HORN BLOWS]

24:35.625 --> 24:38.792
BILLY: Do you know how much I
just wanna scoop you up

24:38.792 --> 24:40.458
and take you back
to New York with me?

24:40.458 --> 24:43.083
JEN: And I would just end up
turning around and coming here.

24:43.083 --> 24:44.250
This is my home, Billy.

24:44.917 --> 24:45.959
So this is really it?

24:46.583 --> 24:50.917
You are leaving me
for a guy who's got

24:50.917 --> 24:52.417
an E.T. doll on his bed?

24:52.417 --> 24:55.083
-It's a collector's item, Billy.
-It is a doll.

24:57.583 --> 25:00.917
Look, Billy, it's been
good to see you again,

25:00.917 --> 25:04.708
but I really should go to that
beach party and find Dawson,

25:04.708 --> 25:06.959
since I owe him
about 400 explanations.

25:06.959 --> 25:10.458
Alright then, before you leave,
since who knows when

25:11.333 --> 25:13.250
and if we'll ever
see each other again,

25:14.166 --> 25:16.000
How about for old time's sake,
you and me,

25:16.333 --> 25:19.959
just one...last...kiss?

25:21.291 --> 25:22.834
One last kiss
and then you'll go?

25:23.792 --> 25:24.917
Scouts' honor.

25:27.667 --> 25:30.083
[WAVES CRASHING]

25:32.458 --> 25:33.417
Goodbye, Billy.

25:35.291 --> 25:37.625
[WAVES CRASHING]

25:42.375 --> 25:46.834
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

25:52.375 --> 25:55.458
[VOICES CHATTERING]
[LAUGHTER]

25:56.750 --> 26:00.250
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

26:00.500 --> 26:03.291
[LAUGHTER]

26:09.834 --> 26:11.708
So, what'd I tell you? Is this
a good party or what?

26:11.708 --> 26:13.500
Oh, yeah.
Time of my life.

26:13.875 --> 26:15.625
I'm ready for the group hug
whenever you are.

26:15.625 --> 26:17.834
Oh, Melissa Fife. 1 o'clock.
That's the girl

26:17.834 --> 26:19.458
of my dreams right there.
How do I look?

26:21.083 --> 26:23.166
Like a before picture
in an ad for geek remover.

26:24.041 --> 26:26.708
Easy, doll. Jealousy's
not gonna get you anywhere.

26:27.750 --> 26:31.542
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪
[VOICES CHATTERING]

26:41.000 --> 26:41.750
JOEY: Hey.

26:42.834 --> 26:43.750
Great party, huh?

26:44.375 --> 26:46.166
Oh, yeah, the time
of my life.

26:46.542 --> 26:48.208
I've had such a rockin' time
since I joined

26:48.208 --> 26:49.291
the JV Football Team.

26:49.291 --> 26:52.208
Oh, yeah, and cheerleading
has opened up so many doors.

26:56.458 --> 26:58.542
What do you say? One quick drink
and we hit the video store?

26:59.375 --> 27:00.458
Thought you'd never ask.

27:00.875 --> 27:02.208
-Be right back.
-Okay.

27:02.625 --> 27:05.375
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

27:08.000 --> 27:10.500
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪
[LAUGHTER]

27:13.750 --> 27:14.500
Hi.

27:15.583 --> 27:16.875
Hey, you're here.

27:17.417 --> 27:19.583
Yeah, I'm-- I'm here,
I'm alone,

27:19.583 --> 27:21.625
And-- and I'm sorry
about everything, Dawson.

27:21.625 --> 27:22.875
About the way that
I treated you.

27:22.875 --> 27:25.583
I mean, I was foolish, and it
was stupid of me to think that--

27:29.750 --> 27:30.792
Come on,
let's go talk.

27:32.583 --> 27:35.917
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪
[LAUGHTER]

27:43.083 --> 27:44.125
Drink?

27:44.125 --> 27:45.166
Uh, no, thanks.

27:45.166 --> 27:46.125
No, really. I got an extra,
so it's--

27:46.125 --> 27:47.917
Uh, you know, actually
my friend's getting one,

27:47.917 --> 27:49.166
so I'm fine, thanks.

27:49.166 --> 27:50.250
Really? Who's your friend?

27:50.792 --> 27:52.792
Dawson Leery. You probably
don't know him.

27:52.792 --> 27:53.917
Sure, Dawson.

27:55.458 --> 27:57.125
Sophomore, currently hitting
the beach

27:57.125 --> 27:58.458
with that cute, blonde chick.

27:59.625 --> 28:03.125
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

28:05.291 --> 28:05.959
Drink?

28:08.625 --> 28:09.792
Yeah, sure.

28:17.041 --> 28:18.792
You know what,
Dawson, I'm sorry.

28:18.792 --> 28:21.000
I-- I know I could have
handled things better,

28:21.000 --> 28:22.875
but I--
it's like Billy showed up

28:22.875 --> 28:25.333
and my judgment just
flew right out the window.

28:25.333 --> 28:27.125
I mean, I cut class, and I--

28:27.125 --> 28:28.291
You're too hard
on yourself.

28:28.291 --> 28:29.458
I swear, she's too hard
on herself.

28:29.458 --> 28:30.500
Isn't she too hard
on herself?

28:30.500 --> 28:32.667
What is he doing here?
I thought you told him to go.

28:32.667 --> 28:34.041
I did. I-- I swear
to God I told--

28:34.041 --> 28:35.667
Yes, but I simply took
the liberty

28:35.667 --> 28:36.667
of reading between the lines.

28:36.667 --> 28:37.667
What are you talking about?

28:37.667 --> 28:40.166
Let's just say as a student
of the goodbye kiss,

28:40.166 --> 28:43.959
it possessed a little more kiss
and a little less goodbye.

28:43.959 --> 28:46.792
-What, you kissed him?!
-It was a goodbye kiss, Dawson.

28:47.375 --> 28:48.834
It was a goodbye kiss.

28:48.834 --> 28:50.875
Alright, if that's all it was,
then I will take

28:50.875 --> 28:52.834
my leave right now,
but you tell me, Jenny

28:52.834 --> 28:54.834
tell me all that kiss said
was goodbye.

28:57.667 --> 29:00.000
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

29:00.000 --> 29:02.041
Alright, not that I care,
but you might want

29:02.041 --> 29:03.458
to pace yourself
with this stuff.

29:04.708 --> 29:06.083
-[SIGHS]
-Pacey, I know

29:06.083 --> 29:06.875
I don't say it enough,

29:06.875 --> 29:09.208
but you're a really
terrific friend.

29:09.208 --> 29:11.208
Oh, okay.
Thanks, yeah.

29:11.500 --> 29:12.792
Is this guy bothering you,
Chloe?

29:14.041 --> 29:15.375
Okay, just a couple of things.

29:15.375 --> 29:17.792
First, her name's not Chloe,
it's Joey.

29:17.792 --> 29:20.041
And second, no,
I'm not hitting on her.

29:20.041 --> 29:22.708
I'm just her friend, God knows.

29:23.375 --> 29:24.583
Well, thanks for the info.

29:24.583 --> 29:25.625
We'll catch you later.

29:26.041 --> 29:27.542
Come on, let's take
a little walk.

29:28.583 --> 29:29.542
JOEY: Bye.

29:30.375 --> 29:31.625
Jen, tell him that
kiss meant nothing.

29:31.917 --> 29:33.708
Dawson, you've
got to understand.

29:33.708 --> 29:36.542
I mean, this is-- this is
such a confusing situation.

29:36.542 --> 29:39.041
And what? Your world is turned
so completely upside down

29:39.041 --> 29:40.542
that you can't even answer
a simple question?

29:40.542 --> 29:42.291
You know what? I think
she did answer the question.

29:42.291 --> 29:44.125
I just think you happen not
to like the answer.

29:44.125 --> 29:45.250
Why don't you stay out
of this, okay?

29:45.250 --> 29:47.208
This is between Jen and Me.
This does not concern you.

29:47.208 --> 29:49.041
You know what? I think that's
where we disagree, Dawson.

29:49.041 --> 29:50.875
Because not only does this
concern me,

29:50.875 --> 29:52.250
it concerns me, gravely.

29:52.542 --> 29:55.917
So, if there was ever a third
and expendable wheel,

29:55.917 --> 29:57.583
in this scenario,
it would be you.

29:58.000 --> 30:01.583
See, Jen and I go way back.
She was with me long before

30:01.583 --> 30:03.750
she ever had even entered into
your fantasies.

30:03.750 --> 30:04.959
You and everyone else.

30:12.417 --> 30:14.959
You know, Dawson,
I may have made some mistakes,

30:15.917 --> 30:17.875
but at least I don't live
in a fantasy world

30:17.875 --> 30:19.417
-where everyone is pure--
-Jen, I'm sorry. I don't wanna

30:19.417 --> 30:21.417
trade insults here. I just want
to know where I stand.

30:21.792 --> 30:23.333
One of us has got to go.
Who's it going to be

30:23.333 --> 30:24.250
him or me?

30:25.959 --> 30:27.583
Jen, who's the third wheel
in this scenario?

30:28.792 --> 30:30.583
You know, I-- I think I am.

30:31.417 --> 30:32.250
-Jen?
-Jen?

30:32.250 --> 30:33.542
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

30:35.917 --> 30:37.000
Are you happy now?

30:38.000 --> 30:39.959
Actually, not too bad,
you?

30:46.000 --> 30:47.959
[LAUGHS]
Are you trying...

30:48.500 --> 30:51.583
Come on. Shh...
Come on.

30:52.625 --> 30:53.875
I hate dancing.

30:54.208 --> 30:56.625
We're doing whatever
you want to do, sweetheart.

30:56.625 --> 30:57.166
[LAUGHS]

30:57.166 --> 30:58.583
[SIGHS]
Alright, Joe,

30:58.583 --> 31:00.583
say goodbye to the nice
serial rapist man.

31:00.834 --> 31:03.291
You again, a-hole?
She doesn't wanna leave.

31:03.291 --> 31:04.959
[SLURRING] I want us to leave,
Pacey.

31:05.333 --> 31:07.000
Alright, come on, cowboy,
part's over.

31:07.667 --> 31:09.083
[GRUNTS]
[PUNCH LANDS]

31:09.333 --> 31:11.125
Oh! God!

31:12.125 --> 31:13.708
-Mmm!
-You alright?

31:13.708 --> 31:15.333
Ugh, yeah. Oh.

31:19.500 --> 31:20.291
Joe?

31:23.333 --> 31:26.000
Dawson, thank you.

31:27.208 --> 31:28.625
You're my hero.

31:32.625 --> 31:35.000
Man, you know,
this is probably not one

31:35.000 --> 31:36.625
of the brightest things
you've ever done.

31:36.625 --> 31:37.500
Shut up.

31:37.875 --> 31:38.750
Dude, we gotta be quiet.

31:38.750 --> 31:40.166
If Bodie sees her like this,
she's dead.

31:40.166 --> 31:41.500
Yeah, I know. Listen,
you two stay here.

31:41.500 --> 31:43.917
I'm gonna go ahead. You
think you can handle
lush life by yourself?

31:44.208 --> 31:46.041
Dude, whatever you do,
don't wake up the baby.

31:47.208 --> 31:48.208
Okay, okay.

31:48.875 --> 31:51.417
All righty.
Okay, we're gonna walk.

31:51.417 --> 31:52.166
Okay.

31:54.041 --> 31:55.166
-[TOY SQUEAKS]
-Oh!

31:56.208 --> 31:57.834
[BABY CRIES]

31:57.834 --> 32:00.417
Hey, hey, little man.

32:01.417 --> 32:05.041
Come on, why don't you just play
like you're drunk Aunt Joey
and uh, go on back to sleep.

32:05.041 --> 32:06.166
[BABY CRIES]

32:07.083 --> 32:10.208
There you go.
There you go.

32:11.625 --> 32:13.166
Let's get your feet up.

32:16.542 --> 32:17.625
Oh, Joey...

32:22.750 --> 32:24.875
I know it's been
a tough week for you,

32:25.458 --> 32:27.500
and you always try to handle
everything by yourself.

32:28.458 --> 32:29.625
[SIGHS]

32:30.458 --> 32:31.959
Is that why you got
drunk tonight, Joe?

32:32.917 --> 32:34.708
Just need a little break
from your life?

32:34.959 --> 32:38.750
Tartar sauce. Tartar sauce,
Table 5, Table 5.

32:38.750 --> 32:40.583
-[BABY CRYING]
-Shh! Shh! Shh! Shh!

32:40.583 --> 32:43.000
Come on, little guy.
Come on. You want that?

32:43.583 --> 32:44.875
Right in there. Come on.

32:48.458 --> 32:49.959
Oh, God, there's got to be

32:49.959 --> 32:51.834
something to
quiet this kid down.

32:55.834 --> 32:58.291
It's probably the wrong time
to tell you this, but, um...

33:00.000 --> 33:01.041
[SIGHS]

33:01.959 --> 33:02.917
Or I don't know, maybe
it's the perfect time.

33:04.792 --> 33:07.250
I realize how incredibly
confusing things

33:07.250 --> 33:08.667
are between us right now.

33:10.291 --> 33:12.417
I can't even begin
to explain our relationship.

33:14.583 --> 33:18.417
You probably can't either.
But um...

33:22.583 --> 33:25.125
I just want you
to know that um...

33:27.041 --> 33:30.291
If you ever need me,
I'll always be here for you.

33:31.500 --> 33:33.417
All you ever have to do is ask.

33:38.542 --> 33:43.083
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

33:46.792 --> 33:47.917
[SIGHS]

33:53.291 --> 33:54.834
PACEY: So then,
the guy who ends up

33:54.834 --> 33:56.291
being The English Patient
and that girl,

33:56.291 --> 33:57.667
they're stranded
in the cave

33:57.667 --> 33:59.125
and she looks up at him,
she's like,

33:59.500 --> 34:01.959
[FEMININE ENGLISH ACCENT]
"Oh, no. Please don't leave me.

34:02.375 --> 34:04.375
Promise me you'll
come back someday."

34:05.000 --> 34:06.667
And he turns around--
Hey, hey, listen to this,

34:06.667 --> 34:08.625
listen to this. He turns around,
he's like,

34:09.375 --> 34:11.833
[MASCULINE ENGLISH ACCENT]
"Don't worry, darling,
I'll come back for you.

34:12.166 --> 34:14.500
Unless, of course, my plane
is shot down by Nazis,

34:14.500 --> 34:16.875
and my face is burned beyond
recognition after cutting off

34:16.875 --> 34:19.250
William Dafoe's fingers."
You like that?

34:19.250 --> 34:20.375
DAWSON: Okay, it's cool
Let's go.

34:21.625 --> 34:24.333
Alright, sleep tight,
little man.

34:25.583 --> 34:28.833
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

34:33.542 --> 34:36.833
I guess scuba diving wasn't such
an inspired idea after all.

34:39.333 --> 34:42.000
Yeah, well, I-- I don't
think that, uh,

34:42.667 --> 34:46.583
scuba diving, water skiing,
or bungee jumping

34:46.583 --> 34:49.500
is the key to solving
our problems.

34:50.041 --> 34:50.792
I know.

34:52.166 --> 34:55.792
I just thought if maybe
we tried something new...

34:59.208 --> 35:02.041
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]
[SEAGULLS CAWING]

35:02.041 --> 35:06.041
I-- I'm not sure that it's the
new stuff that needs the work.

35:06.792 --> 35:10.542
Maybe we've neglected
some of the old things?

35:13.208 --> 35:14.375
Gale, I love you.

35:17.750 --> 35:20.333
And I am willing to do
whatever I have to.

35:24.542 --> 35:25.375
So...

35:25.750 --> 35:26.542
Why don't we just start

35:26.542 --> 35:29.625
with something
really simple, okay?

35:29.625 --> 35:33.000
Something that doesn't
require regulators

35:33.000 --> 35:33.917
or uh...

35:35.083 --> 35:36.250
parachutes, or...

35:37.083 --> 35:38.417
oxygen tanks.

35:39.917 --> 35:42.083
Okay. Like what?

35:42.333 --> 35:44.917
[ROMANTIC SONG PLAYS]

35:46.917 --> 35:48.041
May I?

36:14.959 --> 36:17.291
One thing at a time, Gale.

36:19.458 --> 36:23.458
♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

36:41.959 --> 36:44.792
[WATER RIPPLING]

36:44.792 --> 36:47.625
DAWSON: Ha! Joey was
so out of it tonight.

36:48.792 --> 36:50.792
She-- she babbled on
about the ice house,

36:51.333 --> 36:53.333
kissed me, and rolled
over and passed out--

36:53.333 --> 36:55.083
-Wait, wait. She kissed you?
-Yeah.

36:56.375 --> 36:58.417
She kissed you like
an aunt-on-Thanksgiving kiss

36:58.417 --> 36:59.959
-or she kissed you--
-No...

37:00.417 --> 37:01.500
She-- she kissed me.

37:02.834 --> 37:04.250
I mean, it meant nothing.

37:04.708 --> 37:06.333
I mean, she
was completely wasted.

37:06.333 --> 37:08.625
Obviously mistook me
for Brad Pitt,

37:09.333 --> 37:11.875
-which is understandable.
-Ah, Dawson, my fine,

37:11.875 --> 37:13.166
oblivious friend.

37:14.000 --> 37:14.917
One of these days,

37:16.125 --> 37:17.834
you're gonna have to take a
gigantic fact check, my friend.

37:17.834 --> 37:20.417
Alright, she didn't mistake
you for anybody, okay?

37:20.417 --> 37:22.250
This girl is head-in-the-clouds,

37:22.250 --> 37:25.708
100% ass backwards
in love with you, alright?

37:26.083 --> 37:27.917
-Oh, dude, Pacey...
-[LAUGHS]

37:27.917 --> 37:29.500
Joey and I have
a great time together.

37:29.500 --> 37:31.834
And it's great to have somebody
that you know so well

37:32.333 --> 37:34.375
that you don't even have to
verbalize what you're thinking

37:34.625 --> 37:35.542
most of the time.

37:36.500 --> 37:37.583
The other person just
gets it, picks up on it,

37:38.583 --> 37:41.291
and-- and it-- it's like that
with Joey and me.

37:41.708 --> 37:43.875
It's great, and I like it,
but it's...

37:43.875 --> 37:44.917
I mean, it's not love.

37:44.917 --> 37:47.500
Hey, alright. Don't you think
it's a little strange

37:47.500 --> 37:49.375
that in the middle of a
disastrous weekend

37:49.375 --> 37:51.583
with your girlfriend, Jen,
you and I are sitting here

37:51.583 --> 37:53.250
talking about
your friend,  Joey?

37:53.250 --> 37:55.458
Love is what I have
with Jen, okay?

37:55.458 --> 37:58.208
It-- It's exciting.
It-- It's new and unknown.

37:58.208 --> 38:00.208
It-- yeah, I mean sometimes
it's out of hand,

38:00.208 --> 38:03.917
but trust me, there's difference

38:03.917 --> 38:05.417
between friendship and love.

38:05.417 --> 38:07.875
Right, and you're so sure
that you know that difference?

38:08.708 --> 38:11.708
-[WATER RIPPLING]
-[OWL HOOTING]

38:13.708 --> 38:16.000
DAWSON: You-- you don't know
what you're talking about.

38:22.417 --> 38:23.583
Leaving so soon?

38:24.708 --> 38:28.291
Yeah. I thought I'd check out
the scenery up the coast.

38:28.291 --> 38:31.000
My travel agent says it's
spectacular this time of year.

38:32.834 --> 38:34.542
Assume you haven't tried
to steal anything,

38:35.500 --> 38:36.875
uh, other than my girlfriend?

38:37.417 --> 38:39.708
Hey, relax, alright?
You win.

38:40.458 --> 38:43.208
I just talked to Jen,
and apparently she's not

38:43.208 --> 38:44.458
as confused as she seems.

38:44.458 --> 38:47.917
So, it looks like the nice guy
is gonna get the girl after all.

38:49.917 --> 38:52.458
Oh, by the way,
if traffic's with me,

38:53.250 --> 38:56.125
I can make it up here from
New York in under 3 1/2 hours.

38:58.041 --> 38:59.625
You better treat her good,
Dawson.

38:59.625 --> 39:00.458
I will.

39:02.208 --> 39:05.375
-[CRICKETS CHIRPING]
-♪ [MUSIC PLAYS] ♪

39:27.291 --> 39:30.959
-[CRICKETS CHIRPING]
-[OWL HOOTING]

39:39.583 --> 39:41.083
You know, for someone
who views himself

39:41.083 --> 39:44.750
as a tragically nice guy,
I spend an awful lot

39:44.750 --> 39:45.875
of time apologizing.

39:46.250 --> 39:47.000
[JEN SIGHS]

39:48.500 --> 39:50.500
Jen, I'm sorry about what
I said earlier. Insecurity

39:50.500 --> 39:51.667
brings out the worst--

39:53.166 --> 39:53.875
You--

39:55.375 --> 39:57.417
You know how you're
always curious about

39:57.417 --> 39:59.000
what my life was like
in New York?

40:01.583 --> 40:04.667
Truth is, it's really no
different than it is right now.

40:05.333 --> 40:08.834
I mean, geography aside, I am--
I am still the same stupid girl

40:09.667 --> 40:12.250
who's always found it easier
to escape into a relationship

40:12.250 --> 40:14.417
-than to face life on her own.
-Jen, that's not true.

40:15.750 --> 40:16.875
Okay, it's this
whole Billy thing.

40:16.875 --> 40:20.417
I mean, now that the ghosts
of boyfriends past is gone,

40:20.417 --> 40:21.375
we can go back.

40:21.375 --> 40:22.208
To what?

40:24.959 --> 40:25.875
Dawson, I...

40:28.750 --> 40:30.375
I'm 16. I've uh...

40:31.125 --> 40:33.041
I've never stayed home
on a Saturday night,

40:33.041 --> 40:35.375
I've never gone stag
to a school dance.

40:35.375 --> 40:37.500
I mean, I'm-- I'm...

40:38.542 --> 40:40.083
I'm pretty, I'm-- I'm lucky,

40:40.083 --> 40:41.750
I'm-- I'm fortunate and...

40:44.875 --> 40:48.583
and I am still way too
unhappy most of the time.

40:54.542 --> 40:57.208
I told Billy today that
it was over with us.

40:57.208 --> 40:58.375
I know, he told me.

41:00.625 --> 41:02.875
And now I have to say
the same thing to you.

41:04.667 --> 41:06.959
What? Jen--

41:06.959 --> 41:09.625
You know, I-- I know I--
I criticize you for living

41:09.625 --> 41:11.125
in a fantasy world, Dawson,

41:11.125 --> 41:12.542
but the truth is-- is...

41:14.417 --> 41:15.792
I envy you. I...

41:16.750 --> 41:20.458
Everything is so new,
so untouched for you.

41:20.458 --> 41:23.083
I-- I would gladly trade in
all my experience

41:23.083 --> 41:26.166
for just an ounce
of your idealism.

41:26.917 --> 41:29.000
And I wish I knew some
better way to say this--

41:29.000 --> 41:31.083
W-w-we can make this work.
We can fix this.

41:31.083 --> 41:32.458
-No, no, no.
-I know we can, Jen!

41:32.458 --> 41:34.083
No, it's over. It's over.

41:34.083 --> 41:35.333
Jen, you're upset, you know?

41:35.333 --> 41:36.875
Sleep on this. We'll talk
in the morning.

41:36.875 --> 41:38.250
We don't need to go
over all this now--

41:38.250 --> 41:40.166
Dawson, please, listen to me.
Listen to me.

41:40.417 --> 41:42.000
I gotta take a few steps back.

41:42.000 --> 41:45.875
I've-- I've-- I've-- got to try
life on my own for a while.

41:45.875 --> 41:48.458
You-- you can't just make me
fall for you and then...

41:50.208 --> 41:51.750
bail as soon as it-- I...

41:52.834 --> 41:53.959
[SIGHS]

41:54.333 --> 41:55.417
[COUGHS]

41:56.834 --> 41:58.125
I'll miss you, you know.

41:59.834 --> 42:00.667
Yeah.

42:01.500 --> 42:03.458
I'll be sleeping 80 feet
away from you,

42:03.458 --> 42:05.208
and it'll feel
like a thousand miles.

42:07.625 --> 42:08.417
[SIGHS]

42:08.417 --> 42:10.041
I'll regret my decision
constantly.

42:10.041 --> 42:13.375
I'll kick myself
to no end, and...

42:16.000 --> 42:17.750
and when I come crawling
back to you...

42:17.750 --> 42:19.458
You'll have every
right to say uh,

42:19.959 --> 42:22.041
"Take a hike, Jen.
I'm with somebody else now,

42:22.041 --> 42:23.917
-and I don't need--"
-Somebody who appreciates me.

42:24.291 --> 42:26.542
Somebody who doesn't blow into
town with her dysfunctional past

